##A special report on the epidemic from a global perspective (part I)

Micro-signal Weilu

Function introduction, surround stove, the university student thought, the experience exchange platform. Use Dialogue as a vehicle to discover the interesting world around you. Fudan University | City University of Hong Kong | Chinese University of Hong Kong | Peking University | Renmin University of China | Tsinghua University

(source: US COVID-19 Global Cases, by Johns Hopkins CSSE)

What is happening to people's lives as COVID-19 spreads across the globe? In this issue, 24 university students from different countries and regions share their experiences and feelings, showing the epidemic in the eyes of university students from a global perspective.

Thank you to all interviewees for their participation, limited space, only extracts part of the content.

1
Wuhan student
Wuhan under siege (Source: Google)

"I feel sad and powerless to see my home town the target of criticism. "
Helen, from Wuhan, Japan

As an overseas student in Wuhan, this epidemic really has a great impact on me, mainly psychological and outlook on life change it. Since the flood in Wuhan the year I was born, I have no memory of any major disaster in Wuhan. So in the first week of the outbreak, it was really painful and stressful, and I couldn't sleep. I am very worried about my family and friends in Wuhan. The more this happens, the more I want to be with them. Then there were many voices of Discrimination Against Wuhan and Hubei on the Internet. When I saw my hometown growing up as the object of criticism from netizens, I felt sad and powerless. It's no exaggeration to say that I cried every day during that time, mixed emotions.

This period of time to see everything slowly become planned, support Wuhan medical staff and supplies are also increasing, this kind of uneasy mood has been eased. I began to think about what was most important to me and what I wanted. The emergence of this epidemic, let me know contentment, understand that no matter how high education and wealth are not as important as family and their health. The second is to know that they want to be a person who can help others, in the capacity to start from the small, in the future road as their ability to improve, to help others will be more and more.

Finally, I got into the habit of keeping a diary. For fear that one day will be time and Trivia dilute the memory of all of this, but also afraid of forgetting their own now adhere to things.
"Wuhan is still a beautiful city. "
Bryan Bai, a Wuhan student in Shanghai, lives in Wuhan

I came back to Wuhan on the last day before the closing of the city. I witnessed the closing of the expressway, the bridge and the residential building. I never thought I would be able to witness such an important event. My mood also is from the beginning of panic, to see the outside evaluation of the anger, and now the heart is no longer so volatile, even accustomed to how many days do not go downstairs life.

The study aspect has the certain influence, the school starts from the beginning postpones to have the net class later, the vacation is lengthened, I may develop some own interest. Although I was a little worried about the online course at first, but at the same time I felt very lucky, at least I can still go to school, and the most touching thing is that our principal personally cares about my life on Wechat, which is really heartwarming.

For example, last week when my parents went to the grocery store, we would stand in the doorway and watch them put on their raincoats, their shoes, and all the precautions they had to take. It never occurred to me that such a thing, which should have been so common, should have become so grave as to have the feeling of a warrior going to war.

Finally, I would like to say that Wuhan is still a very beautiful city, I hope you do not fear the Wuhan People, Wuhan people have been trying to do their part. At the same time, I also hope that you can maintain an objective and rational thinking when looking at media reports.

2
The university is located in Hubei
(Getty Images)

"I thought I'd get it under control soon. "
Anonymous, studying in Hubei

It began with an announcement in Wuhan on December 30th that 27 people had pneumonia of unknown origin. At that time, I was afraid to go out, afraid to go to places where there were many people. I was very worried about the possibility of the spread of the epidemic. But there was also a sense that something so serious would have to be controlled as it had been in the case of the plague in Inner Mongolia, and that knowledge of the virus was almost nil, compared to the isolation of homes today, there's still a lot to be done. Came home on January 5th, glad I wasn't infected.

On the 20th or so to do part-time jobs, the next day there are many people on the street to wear a mask, the work is also passive end. The school has already prepared the network to teach the class, according to the original schedule to start school, is a better decision. It's just that a whole bunch of back to school stuff was supposed to happen, and it's all been postponed or canceled.

"All 'from Wuhan' have been treated as pathogens. "
Xiao Mu goes to school in Hubei

I returned to my hometown in Shandong on January 7. After returning home about the second or third day of the Lunar New Year, there are properties to find the door, asked me whether I returned from school in Wuhan. Then a social worker called to ask me for some information, and I begged her not to leak my information because I had been harassed after seeing my classmates'information being leaked. She said yes, and I didn't get any harassing messages, she just told me to stay home and do my quarantine work. Later, it may be the property people spread out, said that a residential area in Wuhan. There was a group in the community, and then it blew up. They were all discussing which building and which unit the "Wuhan's" was. You name it. Of course, these people are too scared, all the "Wuhan" as a pathogen. Actually, I was out of quarantine a long time ago. My Dad was so worried about me, he didn't even dare to let me go shopping alone, and it was only after work that he took me shopping.

3
Universities are located in other areas
"Go Wuhan, " reads the Oriental Pearl, Lujiazui, Shanghai (AFP)

"The moment of enlightenment may be here. "
Leon Ding, a Zhejiang student in Shanghai

In addition to the everyday aspects of life, of course, there are deeper effects. Most obviously, since the outbreak came to light, we've read and seen countless moments of anxiety, anger, silence, and reflection. Some of the daily hidden under the surface of the sea was picked up by the needle, tantamount to every conscience of the young people of blood torture, torture all the crux of the problem, torture what we can do; What these tortures eventually leave behind is a deep and long-lasting sense of powerlessness and tearing, as well as some of the eternal issues that are destined to confront. Every generation of youth needs a rope to climb up from the bottom of the well, a fuse to ignite the enlightenment, and it has fallen.

"Short, selective collective memory. "
Zhuo Ye, a student in Shanghai

It was January 9, and the real sense of "this is so close to me" came on January 20, when the health commission confirmed the first imported COVID-19 infection in Shanghai.

Because I'm studying sociology, I was reading a book about collective memory a while ago, which can support some of the conclusions, such as the sense that collective memory is very short-lived and selective. I'm also interested in how people's values are shaped by a very personal social network called "circle of friends. ". Everyone sees things differently, like my parents'circle of friends, and my classmates with different views see things very differently.

In fact, at home can do is very limited, coupled with the application season, many times for the future of worry and the immediate mix of epidemic, easy to create some negative emotions. But all in all, I'm a very optimistic person. I'm not particularly comfortable with the idea that it's possible to be, both in terms of content and in terms of expression, as an overly emotional way to interpret ideas, and this is a problem that many media outlets expose.

4
Taiwan
On the evening of February 5, the Outer Wall of Taipei 101 displayed words such as "first-line protection partner" , "medical and quarantine personnel" , "refueling in Taiwan" and "please protect yourself" to express gratitude to the epidemic prevention personnel. (Source: Taiwan News Network)

"The triple whammy of schoolwork, spirituality and economics. "
Ivy, the student from the stage

Academically, many courses and projects are difficult for architecture students (or design students) to implement through online courses. Most design departments in Taiwan do not take two different grades of design courses in one semester. They can only take summer courses or delay one year to retake them. Graduates are more influential and post-graduation arrangements may not go as planned. Each subject / school has a different impact, depending on how well the teachers cooperate.

Mentally, Taiwan's decision-making and policy changes have led to serious mental and psychological challenges for the mainland students since January 26. The policy changes every day, and the notifications are almost always dominated by bad news. After Lu Sheng's joint statement, he was attacked by public opinion because 300 percent of the mainland's population in Taiwan is in a vulnerable position (our protection in Taiwan should be the lowest among all people living in Taiwan) . Although some teachers and students in private is to take care of us, but from the overall social environment, the identity of Lu Sheng is still very subtle.

On economy, uncertain factor causes itinerary to be unable to determine tardily, because it is overseas airline or all sorts of reasons, air ticket is a lot can not return. For example, I and my two other friends bought two tickets are now directly voided, non-refundable. In addition, there are various living expenses: rent, telephone monthly rent, insurance premiums even if not used still have to continue to pay, such a loss of living expenses can not be justified. If the unfortunate delay, then in addition to school fees and so on, but also have to include a variety of living expenses.

"The long-awaited exchange was cancelled due to the outbreak. "
Bonnie, a local student from Taiwan

In recent years, the exchange channels of Taiwan universities have been diversified and flourishing, and the exchange programs between students from both sides of the Taiwan Strait have been enriched. This outbreak, however, has hindered many international exchange programs, as I've seen in many cases. For example, friends who applied to Peking University and Fudan University in Shanghai all had their exchange plans cancelled, this has a negative impact on their previous study and internship planning, their future resume presentation and the accumulation of life experiences. There are also friends going to the National University of Singapore Exchange, where the spread of the epidemic has changed all courses to online courses and restricted travel areas, thus affecting the exchange life experience. Friends in Germany and the United States who read the book said they felt differently about the racial discrimination they suffered as a result of the outbreak.

5

Hong Kong
(AP photo)

"affecting all aspects of education and employment. "
KK, Hong Kong student

Because I am a senior student, this semester is my last semester. I need to get my grades up and my GPA UP. However, the commencement date of the pneumonia outbreak was delayed, and the progress of learning was also slowed down. Later, it was changed to online teaching. However, the learning environment did not help me to improve my learning outcomes, nor could I keep up with the progress of learning, this is by far the biggest impact on my life.

He was born on the mainland

The problems encountered by mainland students in Hong Kong vary from person to person. I did not go back to the Spring Festival, but I have a lot of people back to the mainland during the Spring Festival, but now it is not convenient to go back to school, only online learning. Their stuff's at school, too, but they can't come back for it. The return to Hong Kong required a 14-day quarantine, and the school strongly discouraged students from returning.

Grapefruit, born in the mainland of Hong Kong

The impact on learning and employment is relatively large, especially for graduates like me. It was supposed to be the last school year, and there were some Final year projects that were supposed to be about communicating with teachers, but they had to do it on their own because they couldn't go to school. The outbreak has also caused many businesses to delay or reduce their spring job openings, adding to the woes of last year's backlash. I was going to graduate and get a job, and now I'm thinking of applying for a graduate program.

6
Japan
(picture: BBC News)

"worried about being discriminated against for having a Chinese face. "
H. I, Japanese student

Since the shop where I work is often visited by Chinese tourists, the owner encourages employees who want to communicate with customers to wear masks. My ticket for the spring break trip to South Asia was booked through China, but now it's booked through Malaysia instead. I am planning to do an internship in northern Europe next semester, but I am very worried that I will be discriminated against, or will affect the result of my application. I also heard from my boyfriend that his best friend (Japanese) was called "virus" by local children in Eastern Europe! Besides, my mother was very worried that I would be turned away from the hotel because I had a Chinese face. (original Japanese, Chinese translated by the interviewer)

7
The United States
A woman wears a mask as she walks past the New York Stock Exchange (Source: South China Morning Post) 
"worried about my relatives and friends in China"
Allison, American student

I have a lot of friends and relatives in China, so I'm worried about their health. I also heard that some of my friends were asked a lot of questions at the security check of the American airport when they returned from China. Many of my friends had planned to go to China during the winter or summer vacation to volunteer, teach, or do academic research, but now they have to cancel their plans to go to China, these are the biggest personal effects of the epidemic. (original English, Chinese translated by the interviewer)

In addition to the above-mentioned Interviewees, the author also interviewed two international students studying in China, to understand their experiences and views. One chose to stay in China, while the other, who had planned to spend the winter vacation in China, returned home after the outbreak. (the following is in English and translated by the interviewer.)

"Here I can learn as much Chinese as I can. "
Kathy, an American student studying in China, lives in Beijing

Paramilitary soldiers wear masks in front of the Tiananmen in Beijing, China (photo: Google)

The reason why I decided to stay in China, I think the most important consideration is the study. Although I can work and intern in New York and live with my family, I don't know if I can achieve anything academically. I am more disciplined in China, where there are fewer distractions and more time to do what I want to do. It was enough for me to study in China, where I took advantage of being chinese-american and learned as much Chinese as I could.

As far as coronavirus is concerned, being a foreigner does not have a great influence on my life, because I am in China. However, when the virus first started to spread, the American public produced some controversial jokes / emojis / videos attacking Asians for eating wild animals and calling them "dirty" . Asians have been subjected to verbal and physical attacks since the virus spread.

It's interesting to see the differences in the way people approach this issue. On Chinese social media, I saw videos / pictures of people saying "Go Wuhan" and recognizing the hard work and bravery of doctors and nurses.

The continent's largest airline has suspended flights to and from China (Source: Business Insider) 

"When I came home, people would ask me questions about the epidemic. "
Amen Tesfaye, an Ethiopian student studying in China

(I planned to spend my winter vacation in China, but returned home after the outbreak.)

The outbreak affected my college life to some extent. Although I can still take classes online, it's not as convenient as school. E-learning lacks the basic spirit of the university and does not make full use of the resources provided by the university. Another effect of the outbreak was that this unfortunate incident was used to attack my decision to go to China. Ever since I've been home, people I know ask me a very basic question. People instinctively ask me whether I left China before or after the coronavirus outbreak, and no one asks me how my college life was.

Their story is not over, and ours is not. You are also welcome to share your memories with us in the comments section.

In the next article, we will expand our perspective from personal experience to more general social events, focusing on the interviewees'perception of the media role in the epidemic and their different views of current social events.

Conclusion

The SARS epidemic of 17 years ago may have been a long-buried sore to some people, but to the college students, it may have meant a vague impression when they were young. If that was an incorrigible past, the epidemic we are experiencing together today gives us a more tangible sense of being at the center of history. We are no longer the listener of history, but the witness and recorder of the Times. As one interviewee put it, we are "afraid that one day we will be diluted by time of all the memories, but also afraid of forgetting what we insist on now. ". We are aware of the ephemeral and fragile nature of memory, but we still choose to record the mood of the moment, for the dawn of a new hope.

In addition, there are various living expenses: rent, telephone monthly rent, insurance premiums even if not used still have to continue to pay, such a loss of living expenses can not be justified. If the unfortunate delay, then in addition to school fees and so on, but also have to include a variety of living expenses.

"The long-awaited exchange was cancelled due to the outbreak. "

Bonnie, a local student from Taiwan

In recent years, the exchange channels of Taiwan universities have been diversified and flourishing, and the exchange programs between students from both sides of the Taiwan Strait have been enriched. This outbreak, however, has hindered many international exchange programs, as I've seen in many cases. For example, friends who applied to Peking University and Fudan University in Shanghai all had their exchange plans cancelled, this has a negative impact on their previous study and internship planning, their future resume presentation and the accumulation of life experiences. There are also friends going to the National University of Singapore Exchange, where the spread of the epidemic has changed all courses to online courses and restricted travel areas, thus affecting the exchange life experience. Friends in Germany and the United States who read the book said they felt differently about the racial discrimination they suffered as a result of the outbreak.

5

Hong Kong

5

Hong Kong

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
(AP photo)

"affecting all aspects of education and employment. "

KK, Hong Kong student

Because I am a senior student, this semester is my last semester. I need to get my grades up and my GPA UP. However, the commencement date of the pneumonia outbreak was delayed, and the progress of learning was also slowed down. Later, it was changed to online teaching. However, the learning environment did not help me to improve my learning outcomes, nor could I keep up with the progress of learning, this is by far the biggest impact on my life.

He was born on the mainland

The problems encountered by mainland students in Hong Kong vary from person to person. I did not go back to the Spring Festival, but I have a lot of people back to the mainland during the Spring Festival, but now it is not convenient to go back to school, only online learning. Their stuff's at school, too, but they can't come back for it. The return to Hong Kong required a 14-day quarantine, and the school strongly discouraged students from returning.

Grapefruit, born in the mainland of Hong Kong

The impact on learning and employment is relatively large, especially for graduates like me. It was supposed to be the last school year, and there were some Final year projects that were supposed to be about communicating with teachers, but they had to do it on their own because they couldn't go to school. The outbreak has also caused many businesses to delay or reduce their spring job openings, adding to the woes of last year's backlash. I was going to graduate and get a job, and now I'm thinking of applying for a graduate program.

6
Japan

6

Japan

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
(picture: BBC News)

"worried about being discriminated against for having a Chinese face. "

H. I, Japanese student

Since the shop where I work is often visited by Chinese tourists, the owner encourages employees who want to communicate with customers to wear masks. My ticket for the spring break trip to South Asia was booked through China, but now it's booked through Malaysia instead. I am planning to do an internship in northern Europe next semester, but I am very worried that I will be discriminated against, or will affect the result of my application. I also heard from my boyfriend that his best friend (Japanese) was called "virus" by local children in Eastern Europe! Besides, my mother was very worried that I would be turned away from the hotel because I had a Chinese face. (original Japanese, Chinese translated by the interviewer)

7
The United States

7

The United States

A woman wears a mask as she walks past the New York Stock Exchange (Source: South China Morning Post) 

"worried about my relatives and friends in China"

Allison, American student

I have a lot of friends and relatives in China, so I'm worried about their health. I also heard that some of my friends were asked a lot of questions at the security check of the American airport when they returned from China. Many of my friends had planned to go to China during the winter or summer vacation to volunteer, teach, or do academic research, but now they have to cancel their plans to go to China, these are the biggest personal effects of the epidemic. (original English, Chinese translated by the interviewer)

In addition to the above-mentioned Interviewees, the author also interviewed two international students studying in China, to understand their experiences and views. One chose to stay in China, while the other, who had planned to spend the winter vacation in China, returned home after the outbreak. (the following is in English and translated by the interviewer.)

"Here I can learn as much Chinese as I can. "

Kathy, an American student studying in China, lives in Beijing

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Paramilitary soldiers wear masks in front of the Tiananmen in Beijing, China (photo: Google)

The reason why I decided to stay in China, I think the most important consideration is the study. Although I can work and intern in New York and live with my family, I don't know if I can achieve anything academically. I am more disciplined in China, where there are fewer distractions and more time to do what I want to do. It was enough for me to study in China, where I took advantage of being chinese-american and learned as much Chinese as I could.

As far as coronavirus is concerned, being a foreigner does not have a great influence on my life, because I am in China. However, when the virus first started to spread, the American public produced some controversial jokes / emojis / videos attacking Asians for eating wild animals and calling them "dirty" . Asians have been subjected to verbal and physical attacks since the virus spread.

It's interesting to see the differences in the way people approach this issue. On Chinese social media, I saw videos / pictures of people saying "Go Wuhan" and recognizing the hard work and bravery of doctors and nurses.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The continent's largest airline has suspended flights to and from China (Source: Business Insider) 

"When I came home, people would ask me questions about the epidemic. "

Amen Tesfaye, an Ethiopian student studying in China

(I planned to spend my winter vacation in China, but returned home after the outbreak.)

The outbreak affected my college life to some extent. Although I can still take classes online, it's not as convenient as school. E-learning lacks the basic spirit of the university and does not make full use of the resources provided by the university. Another effect of the outbreak was that this unfortunate incident was used to attack my decision to go to China. Ever since I've been home, people I know ask me a very basic question. People instinctively ask me whether I left China before or after the coronavirus outbreak, and no one asks me how my college life was.

Their story is not over, and ours is not. You are also welcome to share your memories with us in the comments section.

In the next article, we will expand our perspective from personal experience to more general social events, focusing on the interviewees'perception of the media role in the epidemic and their different views of current social events.

Conclusion

The SARS epidemic of 17 years ago may have been a long-buried sore to some people, but to the college students, it may have meant a vague impression when they were young. If that was an incorrigible past, the epidemic we are experiencing together today gives us a more tangible sense of being at the center of history. We are no longer the listener of history, but the witness and recorder of the Times. As one interviewee put it, we are "afraid that one day we will be diluted by time of all the memories, but also afraid of forgetting what we insist on now. ". We are aware of the ephemeral and fragile nature of memory, but we still choose to record the mood of the moment, for the dawn of a new hope.
